<span class="displaytext"><b><em>sen. (candidate last) desperately wants to avoid discussing economics</em> </b> <p><b> <em>"ask any of the voters – it's the economy. senator (candidate last), you have said repeatedly, quote, 'i know a lot less about economics than i do about military and foreign policy issues. i still need to be educated.' is it a problem for your campaign that the economy is now the most important issue, one that by your own acknowledgment you're not well versed on?"</em> – nbc's tim russert</b> (msnbc, (PARTY NAME) presidential candidate debate, boca raton, fl, 1/24/08) </p><p><b> <u>this morning, sen. (candidate last) was confronted for his "direct contradiction" on the bush tax cuts:</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) voted against the bush tax cuts, and was against extending them.</b> nbc's tim russert: "one of the questions that has been raised repeatedly in this campaign, senator, is your opposition to the bush tax cuts back in 2001. one of only two (PARTY NAME) senators. back then you gave a floor speech and said this: 'i cannot in good conscience support a tax cut in which so many of the benefits go to the most fortunate among us at the expense of middle-class americans who most need tax relief.' then you were on meet the press in april of '04, i asked you about that vote. i also asked you about postponing the bush tax cuts and this is what you said: sen. (candidate last): "i voted against the tax cuts because of the disproportionate amount that went to the wealthiest americans. i would clearly support not extending those tax cuts in order to help address the deficit." (nbc's "meet the press," 1/27/08) </p><p><b>nbc's tim russert: "now you are supporting extending them... a direct contradiction."</b> russert: "you wouldn't support extending them, but you are now supporting extending them on the radio with this ad: (candidate last) radio ad: "i'll make the bush tax cuts permanent." russert: "that's a direct contradiction." (nbc's "meet the press," 1/27/08) </p><p align="center"> <em>to view sen. (candidate last)'s "direct contradiction," click here:</em> <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zvg4roulsf0">www.youtube.com/watch?v=zvg4roulsf0</a> </p><p><b> <u>sen. (candidate last) recently insisted he wouldn't need an economically-savvy running mate: <br/></u> </b> <br/> <b>sen. (candidate last) now says that because of his experience on the senate commerce committee, he wouldn't need a vice president with economic experience.</b> "noting that he also later ran the senate commerce committee, mr. (candidate last) said in the interview that he would feel no need to select a vice president with expertise in economic policy to balance his own foreign-policy experience." (david leonhardt, "fiscal mantra for (candidate last): less is more," <em>the new york times</em>, www.nytimes.com,1/26/08) </p><p><b> <u>yet just months ago, sen. (candidate last) said he would need a running mate "well-grounded in economics":</u> </b> </p><p><b>in november 2007, sen. (candidate last) said he would choose a vice-president who understands economics because he doesn't.</b> "on at least one occasion, (candidate last) has raised the matter himself. on nov. 10, while traveling through new hampshire on his straight talk express bus, (candidate last) was asked what he would seek in a vice presidential candidate if nominated. after mentioning the ability of a potential running mate to replace the president, (candidate last) said, 'you also look for people who maybe have talents you don't, or experience or knowledge you don't, as well.' 'what are those qualities that you don't - that you wouldn't mind complementing?' asked david brooks, a columnist for the new york times. (candidate last) paused. 'uh, maybe i shouldn't say this, but, somebody who's really well grounded in economics,' he said." (sasha issenberg, "(candidate last) tested on economy," <em>the boston globe</em>, www.boston.com, 1/26/08) </p><p><b> <u>in the recent boca raton debate, sen. (candidate last) denied saying he didn't know about economics:</u> </b> </p><p><b>(candidate last) denied his own comments when tim russert quoted him saying he did not know about economics.</b> russert: " and now the economy has taken hold. ask any of the voters; it's the economy. senator (candidate last), you have said repeatedly, quote, 'i know a lot less about economics than i do about military and foreign policy issues. i still need to be educated.' is it a problem for your campaign that the economy is now the most important issue, one that by your own acknowledgment you're not well versed on?" (candidate last): "actually, i don't know where you got that quote from. i'm very well versed in economics." (msnbc, (PARTY NAME) presidential candidate debate, boca raton, fl, 1/24/08) </p><p><b> <u>but sen. (candidate last) himself has repeatedly said he doesn't understand economic issues:</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last): "the issue of economics is not something i've understood as well as i should."</b> "like (candidate full), who joked recently that he 'may not be the expert that some people are on foreign policy, but i did stay in a holiday inn express last night,' (candidate last) suggested to reporters monday that american consumer culture offered a short cut to expertise. 'the issue of economics is not something i've understood as well as i should,' (candidate last) said. 'i've got greenspan's book.'" (sasha issenberg, "(candidate last): it's about the economy," <em>the boston globe</em>, www.boston.com, posted 12/18/07) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p>- <b>sen. (candidate last): "i still need to be educated."</b> "on a broader range of economic issues, though, mr. (candidate last) readily departs from reaganomics. his philosophy is best described as a work in progress. he is refreshingly blunt when he tells me: 'i'm going to be honest: i know a lot less about economics than i do about military and foreign policy issues. i still need to be educated.'" (stephen moore, "reform, reform, reform," opinionjournal.com, 11/26/05) </p></blockquote></span>



